This means that you'll have to likely create dummy data in storage >= the scale of your existing data. 

You'll also have to evaluate metrics (query performance, inference time, cost/query) using realistic data loads.

For a team that needed instant data access for analytics and modeling, this was unscalable. 

It resulted in lost hours creating and maintaining REST endpoints. 

Access via API was > 10x slower than if we had access to  a fast, query able warehouse.

My major motivation to create this was @GraphiQL, where "prettifying" a query currently strips all existing comments. I'll try to integrate that package in the coming weeks.

`prettier` can print comments, but it also (obviously) only outputs a pretty-printed AST. In addition, `prettier` is a lot of code that you'd need to load if you want to prettify GraphQL queries in the browser.

`print` from `graphql-js` can only output a pretty-printed AST, which might include significant whitespace that bloat the resulting string. It also can't print comments, so if you're parsing and then printing a query all comments are gone.

Because our QA models are designed to summarize a page w/regards to a specific query, it didn't make sense to keep processing a document beyond the first few paragraphs or so.

By limiting the size of the documents being processed, we saw a 2x+ drop in our 99 percentile latency!

Finally, carefully examine your input sizes.

W/all the measurement infrastructure in place, we were able to identify the root-cause behind queries that were sometimes taking 2-3 seconds to complete

Some pages (particularly Wikipedia) resulted in 30k+ tokens for our QA models!

4) Virtual Tables:  Are not stored in a database, but instead represent the result of a query. 
These tables can be thought of as a view of data from one or more underlying tables. 

Created using the CREATE VIEW statement. https://t.co/f0fgZxgUYK

3) Temporary Tables: Similar to derived tables, but their data is stored in a temporary location and persists beyond the lifetime of the query that created it. 
They are volatile data held in memory. ie: The data is not permanent https://t.co/RdHaFjhDbU

2) Derived Tables: Temporary tables that are created within a SELECT statement and are used to simplify complex queries. 
They are tables returned using a subquery. 
The data in derived tables is not persisted beyond the lifetime of the query that created it. https://t.co/UgcnolU5Tz
